# Auth0 Application Manager

Small terminal CLI for creating, updating, and deleting Auth0 applications through
the Auth0 Management API.

Auth0 dashboard "Applications" are called `clients` in the Management API.

## Setup

Use Python 3.10 or newer. The script only uses the Python standard library.

Create or use a machine-to-machine application in Auth0 that is authorized for
the Auth0 Management API with the scopes you need:

- `create:clients`
- `update:clients`
- `delete:clients`

Then export credentials:

```bash
export AUTH0_DOMAIN="your-tenant.us.auth0.com"
export AUTH0_CLIENT_ID="your_machine_to_machine_client_id"
export AUTH0_CLIENT_SECRET="your_machine_to_machine_client_secret"
```

Alternatively, provide an existing Management API token:

```bash
export AUTH0_DOMAIN="your-tenant.us.auth0.com"
export AUTH0_MGMT_API_TOKEN="your_management_api_access_token"
```

## Examples

Create a regular web application:

```bash
python3 auth0_apps.py create \
  --name "Example Web App" \
  --app-type regular_web \
  --callbacks "http://localhost:3000/callback" \
  --allowed-logout-urls "http://localhost:3000" \
  --web-origins "http://localhost:3000"
```

Create with a JSON payload:

```bash
python3 auth0_apps.py create --json @payload.json
```

Create a machine-to-machine application:

```bash
python3 auth0_apps.py create \
  --name "Example M2M App" \
  --app-type mtom \
  --token-endpoint-auth-method client_secret_post
```

Update an application:

```bash
python3 auth0_apps.py update YOUR_AUTH0_CLIENT_ID \
  --name "Renamed Web App" \
  --callbacks "http://localhost:3000/callback,https://app.example.com/callback"
```

Update fields other than the name:

```bash
python3 auth0_apps.py update YOUR_AUTH0_CLIENT_ID \
  --description "Updated local development app" \
  --callbacks "http://localhost:3000/callback,https://app.example.com/callback" \
  --allowed-logout-urls "http://localhost:3000,https://app.example.com" \
  --web-origins "http://localhost:3000,https://app.example.com"
```

The `update` command supports these fields directly:

- `--name`
- `--description`
- `--app-type`
- `--callbacks`
- `--allowed-logout-urls`
- `--web-origins`
- `--allowed-origins`
- `--token-endpoint-auth-method`
- `--client-metadata`
- `--jwt-configuration`

For Auth0 application fields that do not have a named flag, pass a JSON object:

```bash
python3 auth0_apps.py update YOUR_AUTH0_CLIENT_ID \
  --json '{"logo_uri":"https://example.com/logo.png"}'
```

Or use a file:

```bash
python3 auth0_apps.py update YOUR_AUTH0_CLIENT_ID --json @payload.json
```

Updates are sent with Auth0's `PATCH /api/v2/clients/{id}` endpoint, so only
the fields you provide are changed.

Delete an application:

```bash
python3 auth0_apps.py delete YOUR_AUTH0_CLIENT_ID
```

Skip the delete confirmation prompt:

```bash
python3 auth0_apps.py delete YOUR_AUTH0_CLIENT_ID --yes
```
